\i0 \cf2 LEAH\
Several years ago, I started making contact microphone records in science laboratories\'97mostly in a variety of physics labs, but a few other branches of science as well. The contact microphones act as a kind of stethoscope to listen to the inner workings of the machines, bringing out warmer and more internal sounds than you might except from some equipment performing a repetitive or esoteric mechanical or computer-driven task.\'a0\
\
I wanted to use these sounds to make sound pieces that somehow imagined these machines away from their everyday workings, and to use them to create an entirely invisible yet physical space created solely from sound.\
\
To aid me in doing so, I also recorded some synthesizers, myself making some vocal sounds, and some other performative sounds in-studio. This gave me a little more variety of sound to work with, allowing for a more intricate and interesting narrative.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural

\i \cf2 \'a0\
What qualities were you after in this piece ? How did you arrive at them ?\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural

\i0 \cf2 I wanted to make the space created by the sound to shift, constantly: from dense to empty, vast to small, far away to close up\'97a changing narrative with no definitive resolution.\'a0I had read a theory in quantum physics that true empty space is not actually empty, but is instead quite dense and turbulent. I found this paradox quite striking, and\'a0wanted to make a sound piece that was both empty and dense at the same time :\'a0fluctuating between the two, but also, at moments, hopefully embodying both.\
\
I also wanted it to sound as emotional as it does mechanical.\'a0 My sound pieces often seem anxious; I think it's partially a way to immediately\'a0engage a listener and ask them to come to terms with a new sound environment, but is also a bit of a reflection of my own personality. For me, sound conveys an internal, abstract narrative. I like to make that narrative tangible and palpable, but for it to also remain invisible. Combining a lot of different textures and letting them slowly evolve, influence each other, and change completely without the listener really noticing anything has "happened" is one main goal with these pieces, and is done through a lot of editing and re-editing! \'a0\'a0\
\
\'a0\
\
\
\
What is most important for you when producing sound works ?\'a0\
\
I think the most important thing for me in my sound work is, really, creating a very complex narrative that does not resolve in any definitive way. For a long time, I've been drawn to narratives where nothing really "happens"\'97narratives that somehow redefine what an "event" can be. Sound is the perfect medium for this, because it can be so non-representational while also remaining firmly rooted in physical reality and experience.\
\'a0\
\
When do you know that a work has finally coalesced (see how I didn't say 'finished' :)\
\
I know a work is done when I listen over and over and nothing jumps out or feels out of place, jarring, or awkward. Because I want the narrative to evolve almost unnoticed, nothing should really feel too surprising. That said, I also have to be careful that it doesn't get boring, that sections don't go on for too long, and that, altogether, it's an elaborate experience of listening. It's all intuitive, ultimately, but those are the main things I listen for when I'm starting to feel like a piece is coming together.\'a0\
\
\
