\i0 \cf2 At Virginia Commonwealth University in Richmond where I teach, a PhD student, John Priestley, invited me on a couple of occasions to do some source recordings using the University\'92s gamelan. I went for the experience, more than anything, fearing that the sounds would be too distinctly recognizable of another culture and another wonderful form of music that I can\'92t replicate in any honest way. I love the process of recording even if there\'92s no expectation that every sound or every session will be useful. That said, often simple ideas lead to surprises \'a0\'96 when you have little expectation and discover something in the process. \
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural

\i \cf2 What qualities were you after in this piece ? How did you arrive at them ?\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural

\i0 \cf2 After a while we started playing with a bow meant for a different instrument. We were bowing the edges of the gamelan instruments, rather than striking them. Beautiful overtones were produced with beating patterns in the air as frequencies collided. Listening on headphones to the stereo separation, playing the edge of one instrument to the right and then another to the left established a rhythm but also a stereo space that felt exciting. For the catalog/record, I\'92ve also included some more aggressive moments, created by bouncing small bowls and gongs off of a drum-head. \
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural

\i \cf2 What is most important for you when producing sound works?\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural

\i0 \cf2 That\'92s something I\'92d probably answer differently in every context. If there are a few common points to my goals, I hope the sounds have a presence. I hope to find a way to use time and space effectively. Ideally, there\'92s a conceptual element, although I don\'92t always know it from the start. I know lots of artists who begin with an idea. I think I tend to begin with a context and hope that some sort of narrative reveals itself in the action of recording.\
